entry.sense:
OaToraTu AlHaAjibayoni A man destitute of eyebrows; (AZ, Ṣ, O;) as also OamoraTu AlHljbyn; (O;) and some say OaDoraTu, but Abu-l-Ghowth knew it not: (Ṣ, O:) or having light, thin, or scanty, hair of the eyebrows; 
and so TariTu↓ AlHaAjibiyoni: (Ḳ:) the mention of the HaAjibaAni is indispensable; (AZ, Ṣ, O, Ḳ;) but sometimes omitted, on the ground of a weak authority: (Ḳ, TA:) and accord. to Ibn-ʼAbbád, OaToraTu signifies having thin eyebrows. (O.) 
And TaroTaMCu AlEayoni A woman having scanty eyelashes. (O, Ḳ.)

hom.sense:
TirofN A generous horse: (Aṣ, Ṣ, O, Ḳ:) or, accord. to Er-Rághib, one that is looked at (yuTorafu) because of his beauty; so that it is originally maToruwfN, i. e. manoZuwrN; like niqoDN in the sense of manoquwDN: (TA:) pl. TuruwfN (Aṣ, Ṣ, O, Ḳ) and OaToraAfN: (O, Ḳ:) accord. to AZ, an epithet applied peculiarly to the males: (Ṣ, O, Ḳ:*) or generous in respect of the sires and the dams: (Lth, O, Ḳ:) or recently acquired; not of his owner's breeding; 
fem. with p {TirofapN}, (O, Ḳ,) 
occurring in a verse of El-ʼAjjáj: Lth says that they sometimes apply the epithets TirofN and TirofapN as syn. with najiybN and najiybapN, in a manner unusual in the language: (O:) accord. to Ks, TirofapN is applied as an epithet to a mare: (TA:) and TirofN signifies also a horse long in the legs or the neck, having the ears pointed, tapering, or slender at the extremities. (TA in the supplement to this art.)

IAar says, (O,) fiI fulaAnK TuroqapN means In such a one is taxoniyv [i. e., app., a certain unnatural vice; 
see 2 (last sentence) 
in art. xnv]: (O, TA:) and so fiyhi tawoDiyEN. (TA.)

